 [[dispersion relation]] between energy and the two components of the [[crystal momentum]] k<sub>x</sub> and k<sub>y</sub>. However, this concept can be extended to three dimensions, where '''Dirac semimetals''' are defined by a linear dispersion relation between energy and k<sub>x</sub>, k<sub>y</sub>, and k<sub>z</sub>. In k-space, this shows up as a [[hypercone]], which have doubly degenerate bands which also meet at Dirac points. Dirac semimetals contain both time reversal and spatial inversion symmetry; when one of these is broken, the Dirac points are split into two constituent [[Weyl semimetal|Weyl point]]s, and the material becomes a Weyl semimetal.<ref name=Huang>{{cite journal|last1=Huang|first1=S.-M.|first2=S.-Y.|last2=Xu|first3=I.|last3=Belopolski|first4=C.-C.|last4=Lee|first5=G.|last5=Chang|first6=B. K.|last6=Wang|first7=N.|last7=Alidoust|first8=G.|last8=Bian|first9=M.|last9=Neupane|first10=C.|last10=Zhang|first11=S.|last11=Jia|first12=A.|last12=Bansil|first13=H.|last13=Lin|first14=M. Z.|last14=Hasan|title=A Weyl Fermion semimetal with surface Fermi arcs in the transition metal monopnictide TaAs class|journal=Nature Communications|date=2015|volume=6|page=7373|doi=10.1038/ncomms8373|pmid=26067579|pmc=4490374|bibcode = 2015NatCo...6.7373H }}</ref><ref name=\"PhysRevX.5.011029\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.5.011029|title=Weyl Semimetal Phase in Noncentrosymmetric Transition-Metal Monophosphides|journal=Physical Review X|volume=5|issue=1|pages=011029|year=2015|last1=Weng|first1=Hongming|last2=Fang|first2=Chen|last3=Fang|first3=Zhong|last4=Bernevig|first4=B. Andrei|last5=Dai|first5=Xi|arxiv=1501.00060|bibcode=2015PhRvX...5a1029W}}</ref><ref name=Xu>{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=S.-Y.|first2=I.|last2=Belopolski|first3=N.|last3=Alidoust|first4=M.|last4=Neupane|first5=G.|last5=Bian|first6=C.|last6=Zhang|first7=R.|last7=Sankar|first8=G.|last8=Chang|first9=Z.|last9=Yuan|first10=C.-C.|last10=Lee|first11=S.-M.|last11=Huang|first12=H.|last12=Zheng|first13=